# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: payment-gateway-integration
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] A new updated version was developed by Gemplus between 2000-2001.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] In 2001 Arcot Systems (now CA Technologies) and Visa Inc. with the intention of improving the security of Internet payments, offered the **Verified by Visa** brand (later rebranded as **Visa Secure**).
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Services based on the protocol have also been adopted by Mastercard as **SecureCode** (later rebranded as **Identity Check**), by Discover as **ProtectBuy**, by JCB International as **J/Secure**, and by American Express as **American Express SafeKey**.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Later revisions of the protocol have been produced by EMVCo under the name **EMV 3-D Secure**.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Version 2 of the protocol was published in 2016 with the aim of complying with new EU authentication requirements and resolving some of the short-comings of the original protocol.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Analysis of the first version of the protocol by academia has shown it to have many security issues that affect the consumer, including a greater surface area for phishing and a shift of liability in the case of fraudulent payments.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] The basic concept of the protocol is to tie the financial authorization process with online authentication.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] This additional security authentication is based on a three-domain model (hence the "3-D" in the name).
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] The protocol uses XML messages sent over SSL connections with client authentication (this ensures the authenticity of both peers, the server and the client, using digital certificates).
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] A transaction using Verified by Visa or SecureCode will initiate a redirection to the website of the card issuer to authorize the transaction.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Each issuer could use any kind of authentication method (the protocol does not cover this) but typically, a password tied to the card is entered when making online purchases.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] The Verified by Visa protocol recommends the card issuer's verification page to load in an inline frame session.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] In this way, the card issuer's systems can be held responsible for most security breaches.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Today it is easy to send a one-time password as part of an SMS text message to users' mobile phones and emails for authentication, at least during enrollment and for forgotten passwords.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] The main difference between Visa and Mastercard implementations lies in the method to generate the UCAF (Universal Cardholder Authentication Field): Mastercard uses AAV (Accountholder Authentication Value) and Visa uses CAVV (Cardholder Authentication Verification Value).
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] In the 3-D Secure protocol, the ACS (access control server) is on the card issuer side.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Currently, most card issuers outsource ACS to a third party.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Commonly, the buyer's web browser shows the domain name of the ACS provider, rather than the card issuer's domain name; however, this is not required by the protocol.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Dependent on the ACS provider, it is possible to specify a card issuer-owned domain name for use by the ACS.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Each 3-D Secure version 1 transaction involves two Internet request/response pairs: VEReq/VERes and PAReq/PARes.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Visa and Mastercard do not permit merchants to send requests directly to their servers.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Merchants must instead use MPI (merchant plug-in) providers.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] The advantage for merchants is the reduction of "unauthorized transaction" chargebacks.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] One disadvantage for merchants is that they have to purchase a merchant plug-in (MPI) to connect to the Visa or Mastercard directory server.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] This is expensive (setup fee, monthly fee, and per-transaction fee); at the same time, it represents additional revenue for MPI providers.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Supporting 3-D Secure is complicated and, at times, creates transaction failures.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Perhaps the biggest disadvantage for merchants is that many users view the additional authentication step as a nuisance or obstacle, which results in a substantial increase in transaction abandonment and lost revenue.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] In most current implementations of 3-D Secure, the card issuer or its ACS provider prompts the buyer for a password that is known only to the card issuer or ACS provider and the buyer.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Since the merchant does not know this password and is not responsible for capturing it, it can be used by the card issuer as evidence that the purchaser is indeed their cardholder.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Since the merchant does not capture the password, there is a reduced risk from security incidents at online merchants; while an incident may still result in hackers obtaining other card details, there is no way for them to get the associated password.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] 3-D Secure does not strictly *require* the use of password authentication.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] It is said to be possible to use it in conjunction with smart card readers, security tokens and the like.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] These types of devices might provide a better user experience for customers as they free the purchaser from having to use a secure password.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Some issuers are now using such devices as part of the Chip Authentication Program or Dynamic Passcode Authentication schemes.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] One significant disadvantage is that cardholders are likely to see their browser connect to unfamiliar domain names as a result of vendors' MPI implementations and the use of outsourced ACS implementations by card issuers, which might make it easier to perform phishing attacks on cardholders.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] The system involves a pop-up window or inline frame appearing during the online transaction process, requiring the cardholder to enter a password which, if the transaction is legitimate, their card issuer will be able to authenticate.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] The problem for the cardholder is determining if the pop-up window or frame is really from their card issuer when it could be from a fraudulent website attempting to harvest the cardholder's details.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Such pop-up windows or script-based frames lack any access to any security certificate, eliminating any way to confirm the credentials of the implementation of 3-D Secure.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] The Verified by Visa system has drawn some criticism, since it is hard for users to differentiate between the legitimate Verified by Visa pop-up window or inline frame, and a fraudulent phishing site.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] In some cases, the Verified by Visa system has been mistaken by users for a phishing scam and has itself become the target of some phishing scams.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] The newer recommendation to use an inline frame (iframe) instead of a pop-up has reduced user confusion, at the cost of making it harder, if not impossible, for the user to verify that the page is genuine in the first place.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] As of 2022, web browsers do not provide a way to check the security certificate for the contents of an iframe.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Some of these concerns about site validity for Verified by Visa are mitigated, however, as its current implementation of the enrollment process requires entering a personal message which is displayed in later Verified by Visa pop-ups to provide some assurance to the user the pop-ups are genuine.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Some card issuers also use activation-during-shopping (ADS), in which cardholders who are not registered with the scheme are offered the opportunity of signing up (or forced into signing up) during the purchase process.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] This will typically take them to a form in which they are expected to confirm their identity by answering security questions which should be known to their card issuer.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Again, this is done within an iframe where they cannot easily verify the site they are providing this information to—a cracked site or illegitimate merchant could in this way gather all the details they need to pose as the customer.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Implementation of 3-D Secure sign-up will often not allow a user to proceed with a purchase until they have agreed to sign up to 3-D Secure and its terms and conditions, not offering any alternative way of navigating away from the page than closing it, thus abandoning the transaction.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Cardholders who are unwilling to take the risk of registering their card during a purchase, with the commerce site controlling the browser to some extent, can in some cases go to their card issuer's website in a separate browser window and register from there.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] When they return to the commerce site and start over they should see that their card is registered.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] The presence on the password page of the personal assurance message (PAM) that they chose when registering is their confirmation that the page is coming from the card issuer.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] This still leaves some possibility of a man-in-the-middle attack if the cardholder cannot verify the TLS/SSL server certificate for the password page.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Some commerce sites will devote the full browser page to the authentication rather than using a frame (not necessarily an iframe), which is a less secure object.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] In this case, the lock icon in the browser should show the identity of either the card issuer or the operator of the verification site.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] The cardholder can confirm that this is in the same domain that they visited when registering their card if it is not the domain of their card issuer.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Mobile browsers present particular problems for 3-D Secure due to the common lack of certain features such as frames and pop-ups.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Even if the merchant has a mobile website, unless the issuer is also mobile-aware, the authentication pages may fail to render properly, or even at all.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] In the end, many analysts have concluded that the activation-during-shopping (ADS) protocols invite more risk than they remove and furthermore transfer this increased risk to the consumer.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] In some cases, 3-D Secure ends up providing little security to the cardholder, and can act as a device to pass liability for fraudulent transactions from the card issuer or retailer to the cardholder.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Legal conditions applied to the 3-D Secure service are sometimes worded in a way that makes it difficult for the cardholder to escape liability from fraudulent transactions.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Card issuers and merchants may use 3-D Secure systems unevenly with regard to card issuers that issue cards in several geographic locations, creating differentiation, for example, between the domestic US- and non-US-issued cards.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] For example, since Visa and Mastercard treat the unincorporated US territory of Puerto Rico as a non-US international, rather than a domestic US location, cardholders there may confront a greater incidence of 3-D Secure queries than cardholders in the fifty states.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Complaints to that effect have been received by Puerto Rico Department of Consumer Affairs "equal treatment" economic discrimination site.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Version 2 of 3-D Secure, which incorporates one-time passcodes, is a form of software-based strong customer authentication as defined by the EU's Revised Directive on Payment Services (PSD2); earlier variants used static passwords, which are not sufficient to meet the directive's requirements.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Alternative approaches perform authentication on the acquiring side, without requiring prior enrollment with the issuer.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] A patented system called iSignthis splits the agreed transaction amount into two (or more) random amounts, with the cardholder then proving that they are the owner of the account by confirming the amounts on their statement.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] A proposal to make 3-D Secure mandatory in Australia was blocked by the Australian Competition & Consumer Commission (ACCC) after numerous objections and flaw-related submissions were received.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] In September 2025, approval to migrate to enhanced system was granted by ACCC.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] Nevertheless, Amazon can still do transactions from other countries with turned-on 3-D Secure.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] The customer would only be required to pass an authentication challenge if their transaction is determined to be of a high risk.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] In addition, the workflow for authentication is designed so that it no longer requires redirects to a separate page, and can also activate out-of-band authentication via an institution's mobile app (which, in turn, can also be used with biometric authentication).
[src:payment-gateway-integration/3-d-secure] 3-D Secure 2.0 is compliant with EU "strong customer authentication" mandates.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/acquiring-bank] An **acquiring bank** (also known simply as an **acquirer**) is a bank or financial institution that processes credit or debit card payments on behalf of a merchant.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/acquiring-bank] The acquirer allows merchants to accept credit card payments from card issuers such as Visa, MasterCard, Discover, China UnionPay, American Express.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/acquiring-bank] The acquiring bank enters into a contract with a merchant and offers it a merchant account.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/acquiring-bank] This arrangement provides the merchant with a line of credit.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/acquiring-bank] Under the agreement, the acquiring bank exchanges funds with issuing banks on behalf of the merchant and pays the merchant for its daily payment-card activity's net balance — that is, gross sales minus reversals, interchange fees, and acquirer fees.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/acquiring-bank] Acquirer fees are an additional markup added to association interchange fees by the acquiring bank, and those fees vary at the acquirer's discretion.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/acquiring-bank] The acquiring bank accepts the risk that the merchant will remain solvent.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/acquiring-bank] The main source of risk to the acquiring bank is fund reversals.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/acquiring-bank] Card associations consider a participating merchant to be a risk if more than 1% of payments received result in a chargeback.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/acquiring-bank] Visa and Mastercard levy fines against acquiring banks that retain merchants with a high chargeback frequency.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/acquiring-bank] To defray the cost of any fines received, the acquiring banks are inclined (but not required) to pass such fines on to the merchant.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/acquiring-bank] These fees are generally charged to the merchant.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/acquiring-bank] New merchants pose risk to acquiring banks as well, beyond solvency concerns.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/acquiring-bank] A fraudulent new merchant could take a large number of orders, and after receiving payment, disappear without delivering the promised goods or services.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/acquiring-bank] As such, identifying legitimate vs. fraudulent new businesses is critical for acquiring banks.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/acquiring-bank] Due to the high amount of risk that acquiring banks are anticipated to face, as well as their key position in the payment chain, the security of electronic payments is a great concern for these institutions.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/acquiring-bank] For this reason, they have been involved in the development of electronic point-of-sale security standards such as PCI DSS.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/acquiring-bank] Many acquiring banks insist on their merchants being PCI DSS compliant.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/acquiring-bank] If merchants are not PCI DSS compliant, the merchants themselves may be responsible for losses due to fraud, which may result in fines from the card schemes.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] A **chargeback** is a return of money to a payer of a transaction, especially a credit card transaction.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] The chargeback reverses a money transfer from the consumer's bank account, line of credit, or credit card.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] The chargeback is ordered by the bank that issued the consumer's payment card, typically to settle a credit card dispute.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] In the distribution industry, a chargeback occurs when the supplier sells a product at a higher price to the distributor than the price they have set with the end user.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] The distributor submits a chargeback to the supplier so they can recover the money lost in the transaction.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] The chargeback mechanism exists primarily for consumer protection.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Holders of credit cards issued in the United States are afforded reversal rights by Regulation Z of the Truth in Lending Act.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] United States debit card holders are guaranteed reversal rights by Regulation E of the Electronic Fund Transfer Act.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Similar rights extend globally, pursuant to the rules established by the corresponding card association or bank network.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] A consumer may initiate a chargeback by contacting their issuing bank and filing a substantiated complaint regarding one or more debit items on their statement.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] The threat of forced reversal of funds provides merchants with an incentive to provide quality products, helpful customer service, and timely refunds as appropriate.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Chargebacks provide a means for reversal of unauthorized transfers due to identity theft.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Chargebacks can also occur as a result of friendly fraud, where the transaction was authorized by the consumer but the consumer later attempts to fraudulently reverse the charges.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Card association chargeback rules are available online for public inspection and review.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] They comprise a system for adjudicating transaction disputes between cardholders and merchants, primarily where the issues can be resolved based on documentary evidence incident to the transaction.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] The rules provide for arbitration of issues by the card association.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] This may occur where the card issuer generates a second (or "arbitration") chargeback against the merchant, after receiving the merchant's response to the initial chargeback.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Normally this would require the cardholder to rebut elements of the merchant's response.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] The second chargeback results in a second crediting of the cardholder's account for the disputed funds, after having been credited back to the merchant with its response to the initial chargeback.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] The merchant's only recourse after the second chargeback is to initiate arbitration of the dispute by the card association.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] The fee for this is on the order of $250, and the arbitration loser is obligated to pay the costs of the arbitration.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] With each chargeback the issuer selects and submits a numeric reason code.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] This feedback may help the merchant and acquirer diagnose errors and improve customer satisfaction.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] One of the most common reasons for a chargeback is a fraudulent transaction.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] In this case, a credit card is used without the consent or proper authorization of the card holder.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] In some cases, a merchant is responsible for charges fraudulently imposed on a customer.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Fraudulent card transactions often originate with criminals who gain access to secure payment card data and set up schemes to exploit the data.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] In cases of card not present transactions the merchant is usually responsible for the chargeback and associated fees.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] After the adoption of EMV (cards with a chip in them), merchants who have not upgraded to EMV technology usually become liable for chargebacks received (unless others in the payment chain have also not upgraded) even in cases where prior to EMV adoption the merchant would not have been liable.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Chargebacks can result from not receiving credit for returned merchandise, not receiving items they have paid for, or if the items were not what they expected.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] In these examples, the merchant is responsible for issuing credit to its customer and would be subject to a chargeback.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Other reasons include charging the consumer twice for a single transaction or charging an account after the bank declined the transaction.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] For transactions where the original invoice was signed by the consumer, the merchant may dispute a chargeback with the assistance of the merchant's acquiring bank.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] The acquirer and issuer mediate in the dispute process, following rules set forth by the corresponding bank network or card association.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] If the acquirer prevails in the dispute, the funds are returned to the acquirer, and then to the merchant.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Only 21% of chargebacks lodged globally are decided in favour of the merchant.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] The 2014 Cybersource Fraud Benchmark Report found that only 60% of chargebacks are disputed by merchants, and that merchants have a success rate of about 41% with those they do re-present.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] To address these more effectively, technology companies have written code and built algorithms that help merchants determine if chargebacks are legitimate or fraudulent.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Reducing consumer chargebacks is crucial to this endeavor.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] To encourage compliance, acquirers may charge merchants a penalty for each chargeback received.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Payment service providers, such as PayPal, have a similar policy.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] PayPal Merchant charges $20 for each chargeback, when the transaction is not covered by seller protection (regardless of whether or not it is the first) plus it will retain the original transaction fee.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] In addition, Visa and MasterCard may levy severe penalties against acquiring banks that retain merchants with high chargeback frequency.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Acquirers typically pass such fines directly to the merchant.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Merchants whose ratios stray too far out of compliance may trigger card association fines of $100 or more per chargeback.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Merchant service providers may ultimately decline to provide an account for businesses with too high of a chargeback ratio.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Accounts may also incur credit reversals in other forms.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] ATM reversals occur when an ATM deposit envelope is found to have fewer funds than represented by the depositor.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] A chargeback is made to correct the error.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] This could result due to a counting error or intentional fraud by the account holder, or the envelope or its contents could have been lost or stolen.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Chargebacks also occur when a bank error credits an account with more funds than intended.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] The bank makes a chargeback to correct the error.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] If an overdraft results and it cannot be covered in time, the bank could sue or press criminal charges.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] When a direct deposit is made to the wrong account holder or in a greater amount than intended a chargeback is made to correct the error.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Finally, chargebacks occur when an account holder deposits a check or money order and the deposited item is returned due to non-sufficient funds, a closed account, or being discovered to be counterfeit, stolen, altered, or forged.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Banks may sue account holders or press criminal charges when chargebacks are required due to fraudulent activity and insufficient funds are in the account to cover the chargebacks.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Merchants sometimes maintain a record of customers who chargeback regularly, in a "negative database".
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] A "negative database" in the context of merchants and payments refers to a list or database that contains information about customers who have a history of problematic behavior, such as frequent chargebacks, fraud, or payment disputes.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] Merchants use these databases to identify and potentially block or scrutinize transactions from high-risk customers.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/chargeback] The concept of the negative database was notably implemented by Jason Doongoos and Mario Rossi in the late 1990s, specifically in November 1997.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] A **merchant account** is a type of bank account that allows a seller, known as the merchant, to accept payments by debit or credit cards.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] A merchant account is established under an agreement between an acceptor and a merchant acquiring bank for the settlement of payment card transactions.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] In some cases a payment processor, payment service provider, independent sales organization (ISO), or member service provider (MSP) is also a party to the merchant agreement and can act as middle man between the merchant and the bank.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Whether a merchant enters into a merchant agreement directly with an acquiring bank or through an aggregator, the agreement contractually binds the merchant to obey the operating regulations established by the card associations.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] A **high-risk merchant account** is a business account or merchant account that allows the business to accept online payments though they are considered to be of high-risk nature by the banks and credit card processors.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] They will typically pay higher transactions fees if they are accepted at all.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The industries that possess this account are adult industry, travel, Forex trading business, gambling, and multilevel marketing businesses.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] "High-Risk" is the term that is used by the acquiring banks to signify industries or merchants that are involved with the higher financial risk.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Since credit cards were developed in the 1960s, the earliest methods, submitting credit card slips to a merchant processing bank by mail, or by accessing an Automated Response Unit (ARU) by telephone, were initially used but have long been overshadowed by electronic devices.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] These early methods used two-part forms and a manual device for mechanically imprinting the embossed card number information onto the forms.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] This was done by a merchant imprinting their customer's card with a credit card imprinter to create a customer receipt and merchant copy.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] These copies would be taken to the merchant acquiring bank for processing.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Credit and debit card transactions are sent electronically to merchant processing banks or payment service provider for authorization, capture and deposit.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] A credit card terminal is a stand-alone piece of electronic equipment that allows a merchant to swipe or key-enter a credit card's information as well as additional information required to process a credit card transaction.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] They may be connected to Point of Sale systems and typically have a keypad and network connection and may have a built-in printer.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] An ARU (also known as a voice authorization, capture and deposit) allows the manual keyed entry and subsequent authorization of a credit card over a cellular or land-line telephone.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] With this method, a merchant typically imprints their customer's card with an credit card imprinter to create a customer receipt and merchant copy, then process the transaction instantaneously over the phone.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] A payment gateway is an e-commerce service that authorizes payments for e-businesses and online retailers.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] It is the equivalent of a physical POS (point-of-sale) terminal located in most retail outlets.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] A merchant account provider is typically a separate company from the payment gateway.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Some merchant account providers have their own payment gateways but the majority of companies use 3rd party payment gateways.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The gateway usually has 2 components: a) the virtual terminal that can allow for a merchant to securely login and key in credit card numbers or b) have the website's shopping-cart connect to the gateway via an API to allow for real-time processing from the merchant's website.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] For business-to-business (B2B) and business-to-government (B2G) purchases, these interchange fees fall into one of 3 processing categories — Level 1, Level 2, or Level 3.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Level 3 detail refers to passing line-item detail; information generally found on an invoice; PO number descriptions, quantities….other details, level 2 refers to passing tax amount along with invoice/PO#.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Both Visa and MasterCard apply higher interchange rates for commercial transactions that are accepted w/o level 3 detail.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] When set up for level 3 processing transactions over $5,984.61 government, $8725 non-government, are eligible for high ticket interchange rates.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Interchange varies from .50-1.45% depending on the type of card and size of the ticket.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Marketing details are by card issuers like Visa and MasterCard and are enforced by various rules and fines.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] A bank that has a merchant processing relationship with Visa and MasterCard, also known as a **member bank**, can issue merchant accounts directly to merchants.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] To reduce risk, some banks limit approval to merchants in their geographical area, those with a physical retail storefront, or those that have been in business for two years or more.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] To market merchant accounts, an ISO/MSP must be sponsored by a member bank.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] This sponsorship requires that the bank verify the financial stability and suitability of the company that will be marketing on its behalf.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The ISO/MSP must also pay a fee to be registered with Visa and MasterCard and must comply with regulations in how they may market merchant accounts and the use of trademarks of Visa and MasterCard.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] One way to verify if an ISO/MSP is in compliance is to check a website or any other marketing material for a disclosure "company is a registered ISO/MSP of bank, town, state.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] This disclosure is required by both Visa and MasterCard and will cause a penalty of up to $25,000 if it is not clearly visible.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] In almost all cases, if there is no disclosure, the company is likely to be an uninformed fourth party or worse.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] A merchant account has a variety of fees, some periodic, others charged on a per-item or percentage basis.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Some fees are set by the merchant account provider, but the majority of the per-item and percentage fees are passed through the merchant account provider to the credit card issuing bank according to a schedule of rates called interchange fees, which are set by Visa, Discover, and MasterCard.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Interchange fees vary depending on card type and the circumstances of the transaction.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] For example, if a transaction is made by swiping a card through a credit card terminal it will be in a different category than if it were keyed in manually.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The discount rate comprises a number of dues, fees, assessments, network charges and mark-ups merchants are required to pay for accepting credit and debit cards, the largest of which by far is the interchange fee.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Each bank or ISO/MSP has real costs in addition to the wholesale interchange fees and creates profit by adding a mark-up to all the fees mentioned above.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] There are a number of price models banks and ISOs/MSPs used to bill merchants for the services rendered.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The three-tier pricing is the most popular pricing method and the simplest system for most merchants to understand, if not the most transparent.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The newer six-tier pricing, including additional tiers covering debit, business, or international cards is gaining in popularity.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] In three-tier pricing, the merchant account provider groups the transactions into three groups (tiers) and assigns a rate to each tier based on a criterion established for each tier.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] A possible drawback from the merchant's perspective is that these "tiers" or "buckets" are variable from one processor to the next prohibiting any direct comparison from a tier-one provided by one provider to a tier-one provided by another provider.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] A qualified rate is the percentage rate a merchant will be charged whenever they accept a regular consumer credit card and process it in a manner defined as "standard" by their merchant account provider using an approved credit card processing solution.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] This is usually the lowest rate a merchant will incur when accepting a credit card.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The qualified rate is also the rate commonly quoted to a merchant when they inquire about pricing.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The qualified rate is created based on the way a merchant will be accepting a majority of their credit cards.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] For example, for an Internet merchant, the Internet interchange categories will be defined as qualified, while for a physical retailer only transactions swiped through or read by their terminal in an ordinary manner will be defined as qualified.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Also known as a partially qualified rate, the mid-qualified rate is the percentage rate a merchant will be charged whenever they accept a credit card that does not qualify for the lowest rate (the qualified rate).
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] A mid-qualified rate is higher than a qualified rate.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Some of the transactions that are usually grouped into the mid-qualified tier can cost the provider more in interchange costs, so the merchant account providers do make a markup on these rates.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The use of "rewards cards" can be as high as 40% of transactions.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] So it is important that the financial impact of this fee be understood.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The non-qualified rate is usually the highest percentage rate a merchant will be charged whenever they accept a credit card.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] In most cases, all transactions that are not qualified or mid-qualified will fall to this rate.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] A non-qualified rate can be significantly higher than a qualified rate and can cost the provider much more in interchange costs, so the merchant account providers do make a markup on these rates.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] As a result of the Walmart Settlement and to compete against PIN-based debit cards (which are processed outside of the Visa and MasterCard networks), Visa and MasterCard lowered the interchange rates for debit cards well below those for credit cards.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Some providers can pass on the lower cost of these cards directly to merchants.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Consequently, the three tiers programs have added two classifications for debit cards that are processed without a PIN or with a PIN for a total of six rate classifications.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Some providers offer merchant account services priced on an "interchange plus" basis.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] These accounts are based on the "interchange" tables published by both Visa and MasterCard MasterCard.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] This type of pricing creates a discount rate by adding interchange rates plus a percentage and authorization fees.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] This is a common pricing model for very low and very high-average tickets.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The authorization fee (actually an authorization *request* fee) is charged each time a transaction is sent to the card-issuing bank to be authorized.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The fee applies whether or not the request is approved.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Note this is not the same as a transaction fee.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The transaction fee is charged when you accept your authorization.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] This fee only applies to an authorization that is accepted without error.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The statement fee is a monthly fee associated with the monthly statement that is sent to the merchant at the end of each monthly processing cycle.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] This statement shows how much processing was done by the merchant during the month and what fees were incurred as a result.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Many times, the statement fee is not directly linked to "paper" statements but rather general overhead.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] This means that a provider would not waive this fee if a merchant chose to have a "paperless" statement.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The monthly minimum fee is a way to ensure that merchants pay a minimum amount in fees each month to cover costs from the provider to maintain the account.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] If a merchant's fees do not equal or exceed the monthly minimum they will be charged the difference up to the monthly minimum.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] A merchant has signed a contract with a $25.00 monthly minimum fee.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] If all the fees (clarity: this is only for processing costs, so it does not include monthly fees, chargeback fees, etc.) for the most recent month of processing total only $15.00, this merchant will be charged an additional $10.00 to meet their monthly minimum requirements.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Sometimes there are fees that are charged that are not a part of the monthly minimum, such as statement fees.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] It is industry standard to charge a monthly minimum, though not all acquirers charge this, nor do all that do charge it for every agreement.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] A batch fee (also known as a batch-header fee) can be charged to a merchant whenever the merchant "settles" their terminal.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Settling a terminal, also known as "batching", is when a merchant sends their completed transactions for the day to their acquiring bank for payment.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Some providers perform this automatically.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] It is important to close a batch every 24 hours or a higher rate will be assessed by Visa, Discover or MasterCard.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The term "batch header" originally came from the processing pre-electronic terminal era, when each batch of credit card receipts was turned into the merchant's local bank for deposit.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The batch header was a mini-report summarizing those receipts bundled within.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The customer service fee (also known as a maintenance fee) can be charged by some providers to pay for the cost of customer service.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Also referred to as a "merchant support fee", "customer support fee", or simply, "service fee" by some merchant providers.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The annual fee can be charged by some providers to pay for the costs of maintaining the merchant's account.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] These fees in cases include a Payment Card Industry (PCI) compliance fee, which may include a cyber/breach insurance policy.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The early termination fee can be charged by some providers if the merchant ends the contract before the end of the contract term.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] While contract terms of one-to-three years are typical, some providers have terms of up to five years with a one-year prior notice to cancel or the fee will be assessed.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Some providers also assess all statement fees and monthly minimums remaining when the contract is terminated.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Some providers may also assess a "lost profit" fee based on an assumption of profits they concluded they would have earned during the full term of the contract.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Chargebacks are the largest risk that is presented to banks and providers.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] This is not to be confused with refunds, which are simply a merchant refunding a transaction.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] In the Visa, Discover, and MasterCard rules, the merchant's processing bank is 100% responsible for all the transactions that the merchant performs.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] This can leave the provider open to millions of dollars of potential losses if the merchant operates in an illegal or risky manner and generates many chargebacks.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The providers pass this cost on to the merchant, but if the merchant is fraudulent or simply does not have the money, the provider must pay all the costs to make the cardholder 'whole'.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The chargeback risk is the largest part taken into consideration during the contract application and underwriting process.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Some banks are much more stringent than others when assessing a merchant's chargeback risk.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] If a merchant encounters a chargeback they may be assessed a fee by their acquiring bank.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] A potential chargeback is presented on behalf of the card holder's bank to the merchant's credit card processing bank.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Currently, both Visa and MasterCard require all merchants to maintain no more than 1% of dollar volume processed to be chargebacks.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] If the percentage goes above, there are penalties starting at $5,000 – $25,000 charged to the merchant's processing bank and ultimately passed on to the merchant.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] In all cases, a chargeback will cost the merchant a chargeback fee, typically $15–$30, plus the cost of the transaction and the amount processed.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] On October 1, 2011, new rules, resulting from the Durbin Amendment, went into effect that lower the debit card interchange fees the Visa and MasterCard networks charge merchants.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] The new rules apply only to debit cards issued by banks with more than $10 billion in total assets.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Prior to the implementation of the Durbin Amendment, the swipe fee for a debit card transaction averaged 44 cents.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/merchant-account] Under Durbin, the Federal Reserve has set a cap of .05% + 21 cents per transaction (22 cents if the card has security features).
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] A **payment gateway** is a merchant service provided by an e-commerce application service provider that authorizes credit card or direct payment processing for e-businesses, online retailers, bricks and clicks, or traditional brick and mortar.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] The payment gateway may be provided by a bank to its customers, but can be provided by a specialised financial service provider as a separate service, such as a payment service provider.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] A payment gateway facilitates a payment transaction by the transfer of information between a payment portal (such as a website, mobile phone or interactive voice response service) and the front end processor or acquiring bank.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] Payment gateways are a service that helps merchants initiate e-commerce, in-app, and point of sale payments for a broad variety of payment methods.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] The gateway is not directly involved in the money flow; typically it is a web server to which a merchant's website or POS system is connected.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] A payment gateway often connects several acquiring banks and payment methods under one system.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] When a customer orders a product from a payment gateway-enabled merchant, the payment gateway performs a variety of tasks to process the transaction.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] The payment gateway may allow transaction data to be sent directly from the customer's browser to the gateway, bypassing the merchant's systems, using redirect or iframe.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] This reduces the merchant's PCI DSS compliance obligations without redirecting the customer away from the website.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] The merchant forwards the transaction details to their payment gateway.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] The payment gateway converts the message from XML to ISO 8583 or a variant message format (format understood by EFT Switches) and then forwards the transaction information to the payment processor used by the merchant's acquiring bank.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] The payment processor forwards the transaction information to the card association (e.g.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] Visa, Mastercard), which may act as the issuing bank or route the transaction to the correct card issuing bank.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] The issuing bank validates the request and sends a response back to the payment processor with a response code to indicate whether the request was approved or denied, along with the reason why the transaction failed if applicable.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] Meanwhile, the credit card issuer holds an authorization associated with that merchant and consumer for the approved amount.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] The payment processor forwards the response to the payment gateway, who forwards it to the website.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] The entire process typically takes 2–3 seconds.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] The merchant then fulfills the order and the above process can be repeated but this time to "clear" the authorization by consummating (e.g. fulfilling) the transaction.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] This results in the issuing bank "clearing" the "auth" (i.e. moves auth-hold to a debit) and prepares them to settle with the merchant acquiring bank.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] The merchant submits all their approved authorizations, in a "batch" at the end of the day, to their acquiring bank for settlement via its processor.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] This typically reduces or "clears" the corresponding "auth" if it has not been explicitly "cleared".
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] The acquiring bank makes the batch settlement request of the credit card issuer.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] The credit card issuer makes a settlement payment to the acquiring bank (the next day in most cases).
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] The acquiring bank subsequently deposits the total of the approved funds into the merchant's nominated account (the same day or next day).
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] This could be an account with the acquiring bank if the merchant does their banking with the same bank, or an account with another bank.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] The entire process from authorization to settlement to funding typically takes 3 days.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] Many payment gateways also provide tools to automatically screen orders for fraud and calculate tax in real time prior to the authorization request being sent to the processor.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] Tools to detect fraud include geolocation, velocity pattern analysis, OFAC list lookups, 'deny-list' lookups, delivery address verification, computer finger printing technology, identity morphing detection, and basic AVS checks.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-gateway] Some payment gateways offer white label services, which allow payment service providers, e-commerce platforms, ISOs, resellers, or acquiring banks to fully brand the payment gateway’s technology as their own.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] A **payment processor** is a system that enables financial transactions, commonly employed by a merchant, to handle transactions with customers from various channels such as credit cards and debit cards or bank accounts.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] They are usually broken down into two types: front-end and back-end.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] Front-end processors have connections to various card associations and supply authorization and settlement services to the merchant banks' merchants.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] Back-end processors accept settlements from front-end processors and, via the Federal Reserve Bank for example, move the money from the issuing bank to the merchant bank.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] In an operation that will usually take a few seconds, the payment processor will both check the details received by forwarding them to the respective card's issuing bank or card association for verification, and also carry out a series of anti-fraud measures against the transaction.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] Additional parameters, including the card's country of issue and its previous payment history, are also used to gauge the probability of the transaction being approved.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] Once the payment processor has received confirmation that the credit card details have been verified, the information is relayed back via the payment gateway to the merchant, who will then complete the payment transaction.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] If verification is denied by the card association, the payment processor will relay the information to the merchant, who will then decline the transaction.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] After centuries of using metal coins, paper currency made its first appearance in China during the Tang dynasty (around the 10th century AD) and was later introduced to the West in the 17th century.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] Also in the 17th century, people began to use checks as a payment method, which grew in popularity from the 1800s to the early 1900s.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] To help streamline and centralize the multiple types of currency, the U.S.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] Congress passed the Federal Reserve Act in 1913.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] The first payment card was created in 1950 by Ralph Schneider and Frank McNamara to allow members to use charge cards at their Diners’ Club, and consumers were required to pay their bill in full each month.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] In 1959, American Express created the first credit card that allowed users to carry a balance from month to month.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] The ATM emerged in the 1960s and 1970s as part of the growing movement toward “self-service” technology.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] ATMs provided the first technology-enabled banking option that allowed consumers to conveniently deposit and withdraw cash, without being restricted to a particular bank location or business hours.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] In 1972, the first Automated Clearinghouse (ACH) association was formed in California in response to bank industry concerns that widespread check usage would outpace the technology needed to process them.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] ACH became the primary method of electronic funds transfer (EFT) for agencies, businesses, and individuals to pay or collect money online, and is still commonly used today.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] Over the following decades, the evolution of payment technology accelerated.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] The first digital currency is attributed to an algorithm developed by David Chaum in 1983.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] The first online payment processing company was founded in 1998, first under the name Confinity, which was later changed to X.com, changing again to its current name, PayPal, in 2001.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] The market continued to expand over the following two decades, branching out into a full payment processing ecosystem that includes card companies, digital wallets and apps, cryptocurrencies, payments software platforms and gateways, eCommerce partnerships, and peer-to-peer payments.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] Other technologies that are vital to the payment ecosystem are data security systems and processes, automated functionality, and customer engagement tools.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] Due to the many regulatory requirements levied on businesses, the modern payment processor is usually partnered with merchants through a concept known as software-as-a-service (SaaS).
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] These cloud-based features occur regardless of origination through the payment processor's integrated receivables management platform.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] This results in cost reductions, accelerated time-to-market, and improved transaction processing quality.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] Electronic payments are highly susceptible to fraud and abuse.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] Liability for misuse of credit card data can expose the merchant to significant financial loss if they were to attempt to manage such risks on their own.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] One way to lower this cost and liability exposure is to segment the transaction of the sale from the payment of the amount due.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] Many merchants offer subscription services, which require payment from a customer every month.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] SaaS payment processors relieve the responsibility of the management of recurring payments from the merchant and maintain safe and secure the payment information, passing back to the merchant a payment "token" or unique placeholder for the card data.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] Through Tokenization, merchants are able to use this token to process charges, perform refunds, or void transactions without ever storing the payment card data, which can help to make the merchant system PCI-compliant.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] Tokenization can be either local (on the merchant's system) or remote (on the service provider's system); the latter provides a higher level of security against a breach.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] Another method of protecting payment card data is Point to Point Encryption, which encrypts cardholder data so that clear text payment information is not accessible within the merchant's system in the event of a data breach.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] Some payment processors also specialize in high-risk processing for industries that are subject to frequent chargebacks, such as adult video distribution.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] The typical network architecture for modern online payment systems is a chain of service providers, each providing unique value to the payment transaction, and each adding cost to the transaction: merchant, point-of-sale (PoS) software as a service (SaaS), aggregator, credit card network, and bank.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] The merchant can be a brick-and-mortar outlet or an online outlet.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] The PoS SaaS provider is usually a smaller company that provides customer support to the merchant and is the receiver of the merchant's transactions.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] The PoS provider represents the aggregator to merchants.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] The PoS provider transaction volumes are small compared to the aggregator transaction volumes, so a direct connection to the major credit card networks is not warranted, because of the low traffic.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] Additionally, the merchant does not handle enough traffic to warrant a direct connection to the aggregator.
[src:payment-gateway-integration/payment-processor] In this way, scope and responsibilities are divided among the various business partners to easily manage the technical issues that arise.
